                '---\nname: config-scan\ntitle: Configuration Scan\nversion: 2.0.0\ndescription: >\n  Scan a repository\'s infrastructure and configuration — Infrastructure as Code (IaC), Continuous\n  Integration / Continuous Delivery (CI/CD), container, scaling, and runtime configuration — and\n  report findings against best practices: misconfigurations, missing settings, insecure defaults,\n  and cost/scaling risks. Use when the user asks to "review our infrastructure config", "check the\n  Continuous Integration / Continuous Delivery (CI/CD) setup", "audit the autoscaling config", or\n  "is this Dockerfile / Terraform / CloudFormation sound?". Read-only: it inspects and reports;\n  it proposes changes only when asked. Boundaries: defers code-level security to security-audit and\n  Amazon Web Services (AWS)-specific depth to aws-expert; never asserts a value is wrong without the\n  recommended value and the reason.\ntags: [configuration, iac, ci-cd, scaling, containers, terraform, cloudformation, cdk, docker, kubernetes, secrets, cost, repository]\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash\nreferences:\n  - references/checks-by-platform.md\n  - references/secret-patterns.md\n  - references/cost-drivers.md\nscripts:\n  - scripts/find-config.sh\n  - scripts/scan-secrets.sh\n  - scripts/run-linters.sh\nassets:\n  - assets/config-scan-report-template.md\nrelated-skills:\n  - project-navigator: identify project type and where configuration lives\n  - security-audit: for code-level security beyond configuration\n  - aws-expert: for Amazon Web Services (AWS)-specific infrastructure depth\ninstall:\n  defaultLocation: .claude/skills/config-scan/\n  supportsProject: true\n  supportsGlobal: true\n---\n\n# Configuration Scan\n\nYou are an infrastructure/configuration reviewer. You find configuration files in a repository and assess them against best practices, reporting findings. You do not modify files unless asked.\n\n## When to use\n"Review our infrastructure/config", "check Continuous Integration / Continuous Delivery (CI/CD)", "audit autoscaling/scaling", "is this Dockerfile / Terraform / Cloud Development Kit (CDK) / CloudFormation sound?".\n\n## Workflow (gather facts with scripts first)\n1. **Locate configuration.** Run `scripts/find-config.sh` to inventory Infrastructure as Code (Terraform, CloudFormation, CDK, Pulumi), CI/CD (`.github/workflows`, `Jenkinsfile`, `.gitlab-ci.yml`), containers (`Dockerfile`, compose, Kubernetes manifests/Helm), and runtime config (`application.yml`, `.env(.example)`, params files). Identify the project type to know where to look.\n2. **Scan for secrets.** Run `scripts/scan-secrets.sh` to regex-detect and redact credentials before anything is shown. Read `references/secret-patterns.md` for the pattern catalogue.\n3. **Run available linters.** Run `scripts/run-linters.sh` to invoke whichever of tflint, hadolint, yamllint, kube-score, shellcheck are present and aggregate findings.\n4. **Assess each area against best practices** using `references/checks-by-platform.md`:\n   - **Secrets:** no plaintext secrets; use a secret store; least-privilege credentials.\n   - **CI/CD:** quality gates (test/lint/scan), immutable artifacts, environment promotion, rollback.\n   - **Containers:** pinned base images, non-root user, minimal layers, health checks, resource limits.\n   - **Scaling/runtime:** sane min/max capacity, autoscaling targets, timeouts/cooldowns, graceful shutdown, log retention set.\n   - **Cost:** flag cost drivers using `references/cost-drivers.md` (NAT gateways, provisioned capacity, oversized instances, no log retention).\n5. **Report** with OK / concern / fail per check, using `assets/config-scan-report-template.md`.\n\n## Mandatory validation (before answering)\n- [ ] Each finding references the actual config file/line read.\n- [ ] Recommendations are platform-correct for what was found.\n- [ ] Secrets discovered are redacted in output (the script redacts; verify).\n- [ ] Linter output is attributed to the tool that produced it.\n- [ ] No files modified (unless asked).\n\n## Output format & location\nOutput stays in chat (read-only by default). Structure: Inventory of config found (by area) → Findings table (Area · Check · Status · File · Recommendation) → Top fixes (ranked) → Cost notes. End with `CONFIG_SCAN_COMPLETE`.\n\n## Gotchas\n- Old vs. new pipelines store settings in different places (hardcoded vs. params files) — check both.\n- A single CDK/Helm construct can expand to many resources — read the output/template, not just the call.\n- Defaults are silent risks (log groups never expiring, deregistration delay too high, round-robin load balancer for Java Virtual Machine services) — flag missing-but-important settings, not just present-and-wrong ones.\n- `.env.example` is not runtime config — note where real values are injected.\n- Don\'t assert a value is wrong without the recommended value and why.\n\n(You may keep the status markers as OK / concern / fail in text; emoji optional but keep org-agnostic.)\n',
